<HEADLINE>
<P>
KEN CARSON; COWBOY SINGER WITH THE SONS OF THE PIONEERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ken Carson, 79, cowboy singer with the Sons of the Pioneers.He joined the 
group in 1942 after its founding member, Roy Rogers, left to make Western 
films. The tenor remembered for the phrase "cool, clear water," Carson sang on 
"Cool Water" and "Tumbling Tumbleweeds," the group's two most famous records. 
Also a musician, Carson appeared in 22 of Rogers' movies as a member of the 
musical group that backed up Rogers when he sang. Born in Coalgate, Okla., 
Carson moved to California as a child. On Thursday in Delray Beach, Fla., of 
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, commonly known as Lou Gehrig's disease. 
</P>
