<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO; WEED-ABATEMENT EFFORT UNDERWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Property owners who have received weed-removal notices have until May 19 to 
clear their land, city officials say. 
</P>
<P>
 A hearing will be held on that date for property owners who want to appeal the 
notice. 
</P>
<P>
 After that, city work crews will begin clearing the properties of those not 
complying and not exempted. The city will charge for the work on property tax 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials say the work must be done before the start of the fire season. 
</P>
<P>
 The weed-abatement program targets overgrown vegetation such as sagebrush, 
shrubs, poison oak or dry grass. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to being a fire hazard, weeds also pose health problems for 
allergy sufferers and are a visual blight, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
 The abatement program extends to trash as well as weeds. 
</P>
<P>
 Property owners were notified in January of the impending weed-abatement 
drive. Official notices were sent earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
 The May 19 public hearing will be at 5 p.m. May 19 at City Hall, 32400 Paseo 
Adelanto. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information about the abatement program, call (714) 493-1171, Ext. 
295. FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041294-0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 031512 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
